
# Check My Math: What if Everyone in South America Moved to the United States?
## I check my math 

>**_The Short Stuff:_** I've said that, if every single person in South America immigrated to the United States,
English would still be the most popular language in the country. Let's see if the numbers hold up!




All of these estimates use 2020, a year that lets us get good data from both the U.S. Census Beuraeu and the Ethnologue Langugae Estimates.

How many Spanish speakers live in South America?

The population of South America is about 430 million [pop-south-america]. However, about 203 million of these people lived in Brazil, where the main language spoken is Portugese.
Of course, neither of these linguistic regions are absolute, with all countries having smaller populations that don't speak the most common language. To make a conservative estimate, 
I'll treat all non-Brazilians as Spanish speakers, while also including the estimated 8-million Spanish speakers within Brazil [cite this].

This puts the estimate at approximately 214 million Spanish speakers in South America (in 2020).

How many English speakers live in South America?

The same source as our Spanish number (*Ethnologue*), has a 2020 estimate of only 6.9 million English speakers in South America.

How many Spanish speakers live in the United States?

Using the U.S. census data for 2020 estimated 40 million spanish speakers in the U.S. (although this data does not include children under the age of five).

How many English speakers live in the United States? 

Counting only those speakers who speak English "Well" or "Very Well", the 2020 estimate adds up to 280 million English speakers in the U.S. [english-in-us-2022]
This number is not counting any children younger that five years old.


Totals

Now let's imagine a scenario where every single person in South America immigrated into the United States. In this new population, adding our four previous numbers would give us a combined 286 million English speakers, and 254 million Spanish speakers.
So even with conservative estimates, English would still be the most widely spoken language in the United States. The idea that English
is under threat of being overwhelmed and lost to the American public is not just false, it's laughably false. Restrictionists imagine a world where
Spanish is so widely spoken that even a slight increase in immigration would end in English literally being forgotten by United States citizens, swept aside
in a country that was 90% Spanish-speaking. There are literally not enough Spanish speakers in the world for this to be possible.

Caveats and Gotchas

Most factoids oversimplify the world, and this tidbith is no exception. It's worth remembering that the numbers I cite here are over five years old, and are somewhat out of date.
There are also different ways of measuring these numbers that produce different results. A restrictionist who wanted to understate the strength of English might want to be more stingy about
who counts as "an English speaker", perhaps only counting people who self-report speaking English "Very well" in the U.S.C.B.'s data. They might also be suspicious of self-reported numbers, or hold the standard of 
"English speaking" to such a high level that even native-born monolingual U.S. citizens would not count as "English speakers" if they didn't speak it properly (the echos of Professor Higgin's song from
My Fair Lady can still be heard on the breeze
!)

Another caveat worth pointing out is that, even if English were the most popular language in America under this imagined scenario, it wouldn't be the *majority* language.
With 200 million portugese speaokers, only about 40% of the United States would be speaking English (at least, at first). Whether this would result in the immediate death of English
is a discussion for another post.

